Happiness Hackers Exposed: The Art of Swiping the Credit for Your Joy 

Have you ever encountered those sneaky Happiness Hackers who try to steal credit for your joy? 

They're masters of manipulation and guilt-tripping. 
Let's expose their tactics and reclaim our happiness! 

1. Picture this: You ace a project at work and are receiving accolades from your CEO at a company meeting, and your boss, Chief Happiness Hacker, swoops in, boasting, "I handled the entire proposal. It was my strategy." 

Don't let them swipe your credit! You worked hard for it & it will only set you up for future disappointments.

2. Watch out for their emotional manipulation! They'll say, "You were nothing before I came into your life. I'm the reason you're happy now." 

But here's the truth: your happiness isn't tethered to their presence. You are free to find joy independently.

3. Now, beware their minimizing tricks! 

You throw an amazing party, and they casually comment, "The party was decent, but let's not forget who came up with the theme and did most of the planning. It would've been a disaster without my help." 

Don't let them diminish your efforts. Own your success and celebrate it!

4. Happiness Hackers have a knack for ignoring your needs and desires. You share an exciting idea, and they brush it off, saying, "That idea of yours is cute, but we should focus on something more practical and beneficial (for me). Let's move on." 

Remember, your happiness matters too! Pursue what brings you joy.

5. Ah, the guilt-inducing masters! You hang out with other friends, and they claim, "You always find a way to leave me behind and have a good time without me. Guess I'm just not worth your company." 

But don't you believe it! Your friendship isn't a game of Monopoly. Enjoy time with others guilt-free!

So, how do we counter these Happiness Hackers? First, see their tricks for what they are: attempts to steal your joy. But, you're no pushover! 

When they swipe your credit, confidently remind them of your hard work and achievements. 
Say (while you imagine a hand blocking their negative energy).

"I'm proud of my accomplishments, and I won't let anyone diminish the effort and dedication it took to get where I am."

"I know my worth, and I won't let anyone underestimate my abilities or take credit for my achievements. I've earned my place."

"I've faced countless challenges and setbacks, but I never gave up. I proved myself through hard work and resilience, and I'll continue to do so."

Embrace your passions without seeking their approval. 

Unleash your creativity and let happiness flow. You deserve it!  

Surround yourself with supportive people who celebrate your victories and lift you higher.

Remember, your happiness is a treasure, and no one should snatch it away. Reclaim your joy, celebrate your unique talents, and live life on your own terms! You've got this!  💪✨

Interesting to see the wide range of opinions on this... big part of me agrees with you here Theo, big part of me agrees with the hackers and customizers who want to tune their experience.

Ultimately I think we shouldn't blame Arc or responsible hackers for the actions of ignorant or irresponsible users who customize and then complain to makers about a problem they created for themselves.

Personally, I use a big display and dark mode almost everywhere, and often when I'm using my computer it's dark outside and in my room.

So for example when I run into a website like @paulg 's blog, with content I love but that doesn't visually adapt well to my screen size and is super bright light mode, I like to write some custom CSS to center the content, maybe invert and hue rotate the colors for a quick dark mode, etc.

Sometimes it's as simple as taking a background from dark grey to pure black.

Makes it possible for me to read on my device without killing my eyes - and I take full responsibility for any bugs introduced through my customizations.

When I build products, I always try to provide users with customization options that fit their accessibility needs, palette preferences, and unique screen, as soon as possible.

There's 100 reasons why I don't want people to carelessly hack around and mess up the intended design and functionality of the product, but if my product doesn't have the options somebody is looking for, I don't think it's fair to be too hard on people who want to provide customization and tuning for themselves or others.

5. The Point

There are plenty of healthy habits out there.

But, you've gotta do what works for you. 

It's better to keep a healthy habit in a way that's sustainable for you instead of trying to do it perfectly. 

Cuz if it's a big inconvenience, long-term, you might give up🫤

4. Sustainability

It's more sustainable for me to begin my showers warm and end them cold. 

So now I can actually enjoy my shower and still get some sliver of the benefits of cold-exposure 

*I shower as soon as I get up, so I don't sleep in to avoid the cold water😅 anymore

1. The Wrong Motivation

Back when I was 15, I thought taking cold showers would make me successful😂

Obviously, I was wrong. 

At the time, I hadn't separated the habits of successful people and the actions that got them there. 

I thought they were the same, but they're not.

2. Science

Does cold-exposure have health benefits? 

Absolutely (I trust @hubermanlab)😤

But, as far as I know, cold showers aren't at the level of cold exposure needed to see many of its benefits. 

Cold-immersion is what many studies explored - cold showers aren't the same.
